Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            Living in the United States and raising elementary school going kids, I'm deeply anguished that despite the richness in culture &amp; traditions of India, our children - be in India or outside - are not learning Indian languages and that Indian literature is in a state of decay while language/literature of the Chinese, Japanese, Koreans, Israel etc. is thriving despite the onslaught from West. Learning English is important, but by focusing on this foreign language alone - historically imposed on us my Thomas Macaulay - we're degrading our cultural ethos and stifling our very innately Indian  ability of being able to imbibe, evolve and express in many linguistic and artistic forms like our forefathers. It should be our responsibility to be good stewards of the body of knowledge in Sanskrit, and all native Indian languages, and it should be part of our value system to flourish that identity of ours by learning and expanding Indian literature. <br/><br/>
Research has proven that learning new language makes the brain more developed as the process of learning language, especially, builds synapses in the brain. Towards that objective, pediatricians in the US urge parents to speak, if not teach, children their native language as they'd learn English anyway. Perhaps this fact, now validated by research, would would convince those Indian parents who berate their children from speaking any other language than English. Hope cynics also appreciate this perspective as there's a growing inimical tendency to paint anything about Indian culture and tradition with a political "Hindutva" brush.<br/><br/>
My new, though late(!) realization has transformed me from once a snob of English medium school - who correlated English accent of Indians to their mental ability - to a humble student of Indian languages who realizes that Indian progress would be stronger the closer we are to our roots. I salute the folks who contribute to the growth Indian literature in all languages. <br/><br/>
I'd been off the topic but given the context, I'm very pleased to learn about MCLI from your blog.
                         </div>



